               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc material="parchment">
                        <support>
                           <p>Parchment</p>
                        </support>
                        <extent>437 folios
									
								</extent>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
									55 quires: i4 (folios 1-4), ii-liv8 (folios 5-428), lv10-1 (folios 429-437). 
									Quire numbering in Hebrew characters.
								</p>
                        </collation>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>
                           <p>Columns: 2 3;
                                                  ruled lines: 31;
                                                  written lines: 31; Uniform layout. Ruling and pricking are visible.Numerous decorations:  2 full-page miniatures of the Temple implements, masoretic lists in architectural frames, masorah in micrographic design.Masorah magna usually occupies two lines of the upper and three lines of the lower margin of each page. It is frequently written in the form of ornamental design, often that of a candlestick.Exodus, Numbers, Jeremiah, Malachi, Psalms, Song of Songs, Esther and Ezra-Nehemiah begin a new column, and Leviticus and Proverbs begin a new leaf.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <scriptDesc>
                     <scriptNote>Sefardi square script, third quarter of the 14th century, punctuated. </scriptNote>
                  </scriptDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="miniature">
								2 full-page miniatures of the Temple implements, in colours and gold.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="border"> Masoretic lists in architectural frames, in colours and gold. 
							</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="paratext">
								Masorah in micrographic design.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding>
                        <p> Post-1600. 18th-century Italian red velvet binding on wood boards, with copper centrepiece and cornerpieces and remains of clasps. Spine: 'Biblia Sacra Hebraica in Membrana. Mus. Brit. Jure. Emptionis. 15, 250.'</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
